  issn = {0165-2370},
  doi = {10.1016/0165-2370(89)85032-6},
  abstract = {The products formed when a polymer is pyrolyzed depend firstly on the chemical identity of the polymer, but also on the nature of the pyrolysis, especially the temperature and heating rate. The relative abundance of specific compounds in the pyrolyzate may be related to the pyrolysis temperature in a linear way, so that a graph of the peak area ratios of these materials in the pyrogram versus the pyrolysis temperature produces a straight line. This has been shown to be the case for Kraton 1107 (a copolymer of styrene and isoprene) and for polyethylene among others. Generally, the ratio is made between the peak for a compound of relatively high molecular weight and one of low molecular weight, with the implication that at higher temperatures the larger molecules are being degraded to form more of the smaller products. Polyethylene reveals an interesting temperature-related phenomenon. When pyrolyzed, polyethylene produces linear hydrocarbons, namely alkanes, alkenes and terminally unsaturated diolefins. These hydrocarbons are typically present in all carbon chain lengths up to 30–40 carbons. The amount of diene generated (relative to the corresponding alkane) increases as the pyrolysis temperature is increased. A graph of the diene/alkane ratio versus the pyrolysis temperature shows that the relationship is linear in the range 600–1000° C. Data are shown regarding the temperature dependence of product ratios for polyethylene and poly(1-butene), as well as the generation of small molecules which may help clarify the pathways by which these products are formed.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {Degradation,poly(1-butene),polyethylene,polymers,pyrolysis,reaction mechanism.},
